text: My first crush. I was 10 years old, living in Las Vegas with my younger sister, parents just divorced.   I was a very Sensitive , but strong will Aries child. Running the strip,  from pool to pool. Living at the lone palm motel. It was the time of my life. My first barbie, wasn't much a doll girl, though I did love sparkles! Loved playing in the desert with the trailer park kids in the early 70's! Mom let us run wild.  I remember the first time someone showed me the album by Elton John. It was too kool, "Goodbye yellow brick road " me, being a huge fan of "the wizard of oz" I used to make people call me "Dorothy " after "Dorothy Gail" I was glued to that album cover. It's one of my very first memories after my parents divorce. Then I heard it. That was the best summer of my life. I even learn to swim, saved a kid from drowning too. (Self taught swimmer) Elton and Bernies music got me through the hardest times in my life. I will be forever grateful. Now, seeing this movie, makes me love him that much more. Ny favorite scene had to be the one starting at the troubadour.  We had moved from California in 74 to vegas, so that place that ride down sunset will always be in my mind. The 70s were a different time. I'm so glad  to be a kid in the 70s. A KID not a teen. A kid! The best time of your life. This movie, brought me back. And I'm loving it over and over again.  Thank you Elton and Bernie. Thank you Taron Egerton!  You played him so well, I remember why I had a crush on him when I was a young girl . Elton was and still is captain fantastic! You did an excellent job. 💋😍

text: Disappointed. Not a bad movie..but not that good. I love "Bohemian Rhapsody", but Rocketman, not so much.BR worked because it focused on telling a story. Rocketman is a very bad musical. A good musical use songs to tell a story. Rocketman take all of John's hits....and throw them all over the movie. So as they are telling a story, you're taken away to a music video, back to story, then to a music video. Bohemian worked because you didn't have to be a Queen fan. You're not constantly bombarded by full queen songs in the movie and when they do, it's in the background. Rocketman bombards you with full songs and could only be a good thing if you're a John fan. Straight out of Compton was great...but imagine if every 5-10 minutes, you have to listen to a full NWA song? It would make the film horrible.  Rocketman is a lot like Beavis and Butthead where you're taking away from the story to watch dumb music videos. Horrible!
author: Ne Ws

text: Be warned: This is a homosexual musical, wrapped beautifully in poetic cinematic genius.  It sadly contains both heterosexual and homosexual soft porn scenes* (that make me once again long for  the 40s and 50s cinematic sensibilities of modesty and nuance). It is unabashedly pro-gay in its overtones.   That being said, it does a helluva job showing the painful family dynamics that drive children to seek love and acceptance in others the rest of their lives, and, all too commonly, in the addictions that are an attempt to fill the hole in their hearts.  It is a gritty, hard-hitting look at the human struggle for meaning and acceptance of anyone who has been abused in childhood.  It is an unflinching examination of the brutal consequences of our poor choices in our search for real love and the denial we bury ourselves in along the way as we cope with the  betrayal of those we should be able to trust.    With a world that has consistently grown more selfish, many,  many people will be able to see themselves (their pain and struggle) in this movie. My prayer is they will also do the hard work neccesary to confront their demons, stop running from their pain and the truths of their lives,  and own their self-destructive choices so as to be able stop the abuse cycle and to find, give and receive true love in this life.  May this movie be an inspiration to the wounded to walk through the fire of honest, hard-core therapy to a place of healing and wholeness.   As a survivor, who is "still standing," and who has run the therapy gauntlet to face down a past that drove me to create my own personal hell, I can attest, with Elton John, it is totally worth it.    (Just know from the outset the scars and coping tendencies remain for life, they just don't control/drive you anymore.  You become much more free to choose your life.)  *My only complaint about this movie, which boldly addresses the horrific realities of addictions, is its use of graphic sex scenes that ironically feed our cultural pornographic sex addictions.  FAIL.  Big time.☹👎👎👎

text: I would very much like Hollywood to do a biopic on Jared Fogle, the former Subway spokesperson and now convicted felon,  roly-poly-boy-toy and daily punching bag for any number of his fellow inmates at the federal penitentiary in Englewood, Colorado.   Perhaps it too could  be a musical.  One of the numbers could be called "Smaller Pants," and two different versions could both open and close the production.  In the beginning, Jared sings "I wanna get in smaller pants," in reference to his desire to lose weight by eating only veggie subs.  At the end prior to his arrest, as he's flying around the country molesting children, he could sing the same line, but it would of course have a far more sinister meaning.   Another number could involve a couple of parents going to the authorities to report that their pre-adolescent son has been victimized by Fogle.  The song could be titled "He Went to Jared."   You see, I'm a dead ringer for Fogle.   We're talking "separated at birth" identical.   Up until November, 2015 I had a fairly steady part time gig posing as him and entertaining at kids' birthday parties.  For a reasonable fee, I'd provide the entertainment (balloon animals and showing the kids the former pants with a 48 inch waistline that "Jared" used to have to wear before he started eating Subway veggies subs everyday) and the food (a Subway platter). Needless to say, my tax returns for the past few years have shown a fairly significant reduction in income. My last gig was just after Thanksgiving in 2015. The people who had booked me had paid a deposit in advance, so they went ahead and had me come out with my balloons and five foot cold cut with six toppings on  Italian herb bread.  I ended up getting mauled by their German Shepherd who had been watching CNN a week or so earlier.   Thank you for dedicating a few moments of your precious little time as a sentient being on earth  to reading this.
author: Larry Stevens

text: It was definitely not better than Bohemian Rhapsody. My biggest issue with it was the frenetic fantasy/dream like sequences in the film. Is this a bio pic or an acid trip?? And the songs weren’t in sequence with the time periods which would've made more sense as it would show his music progressing as he progressed.   There were a few emotional moments meant to tug at the heartstrings but overall, I didn't really enjoy it like I did Bohemian Rhapsody. I think the reason Rocketman got such high ratings was due to the fact that it didn't shy away from the love scenes like BR did but even Rocketman love scenes were pretty tame as I would have expected they'd go all out in Elton John fashion but they didn’t.

text: For those of you wanting a Bowie film, check out Todd Haynes' Velvet Goldmine (1998).       Trailer:  https://youtu.be/PO5q2lfdCC4      IMDB:  https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120879/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt Bowie initially cooperated with the film until he learned the script was based on two unauthorized biographies, one of them by his ex-wife, Angie. At that point Bowie pulled his support, the licensing for his music, and threatened a lawsuit. So Bowie became Brian Slade (Jonathan Rhys Meyers) and Ziggy Stardust became Maxwell Demon. The Curt Wild character (Ewan McGregor) is an amalgamation of mostly Iggy Pop with bits of Lou Reed, and Angie became Mandy (Toni Collette). Christian Bale plays a fictional reporter piecing the story together.

text: Grew up with Elton all my life since the 70's, now in my 60's. I have all his records and cd's and tapes! But when I saw his tickets prices for his last final tour that will last I think for 3 years, and coming to my city, I almost Died! I understand all the fees that need to be paid to staff, etc. but those Prices...OMG, even for the cheapest ticket was a Joke!@ I wouldn't even pay that much if God was in concert! But then again God would not charge anything! I Love you Elton all my life...but I am SURE you don't have to STICK it to the Fans in your final tour! I'm am sure you could have made better deals with everyone involved for your LOYAL fans! The ones that made you RICH and Famous! The fans that gave you every material thing on earth that you ever wanted! The fans that stuck with you and your music (and Bernie's) from the very beginning! You'd probably not be anything anyways without Bernie! Well I will still listen to your music till I die (but probably not as much as I use to), but maybe more when I get over this Killing you want to make from the FANS! Ok, done ranting.....even though the concert would be worth it to pay and see Elton's ticket prices, I would Never, ever! Also the actor playing Elton in this movie looks No Way like Elton compared to the Freddy Mercury actor. I think they could have found a Better Elton actor! I guess the movie producers wanted to Hurry and start filling Elton's moneybags quicker than a Rocket, Man....Hey, Rocketman!! Wow.

text: I thought 'Rocketman' was average at best.  I didn't hate it.  But it seemed as though the filmmakers tried so hard to break the biopic mold by having people break out in song and dance every time they were in danger of committing the 'biopic cliche crime'.  It was too distracting for me.  The song/dance breaks felt like an excuse rather than a natural extension of the scene.  To me, 'La La Land' is the perfect mold for how a musical should be done.  The singing and dancing was used sparingly and only when the scene absolutely demanded it.  Anyway, I personally felt that 'Bohemian Rhapsody' was a better film.  It's too bad filmmakers are so beholden to the pompous critics.  In bending over backwards to appease the critics, they only suck the joy out of film.

text: Got to see the film last night and was blown away.   I was honestly not a big Elton John fan, I always admired him for living out loud and never being afraid to be himself, but his music didn't do much for me.   After seeing his movie, I have a new appreciation for his music and for him.  His story is so compelling and the way the movie was made is very unique with the transitions between scenes and the musical performances.   Taron Egerton is so great as Elton including with all the singing.   Even if you are not a fan of his music I highly recommend seeing this movie.    It really moved me emotionally and I was not expecting that at all.

Definitely an awesome film.

text: Saw this tonight at an early screening. Was a very fun and enjoyable movie. Taron Egerton's singing is excellent and his performance is amazing. Unlike Bohemian Rhapsody, they don't try to cover up the low points of Elton's life. It being a musical also helps to let us hear more of the songs. The songs also usually had to do with the plot and weren't thrown in willy nilly, which was nice. Bernie Taupin also gets his fair share of credit. My dad, who had seen Elton John on his first American tour, really enjoyed it as well. Highly recommend.   Also, can people shut up about the gay sex scene? It's 15 seconds and there's zero nudity. You forget it happened 5 minutes later. Clam down.

text: Here's something I noticed in this trailer. There are a few moments which are straight from real documented parts of Elton's life, like the music video to "Don't Go Breaking My Heart" at 0:59 and his wedding to Renate Blauel at 1:51. In these scenes, little details are off, like Elton's suit patterns, Kiki's dungarees, and Renate's dress color. I feel like this is supposed to be part of the "fantasy" element of the film. It's not a frame-for-frame recreation, but rather Elton's life filtered through his own vision.    If the film has any nuance like that, I'm going to love it! As many people have already pointed out, music biopics are very formulaic, to the point of parody. I'm glad this movie is going to have an R-rating so it can be an authentic view of his life, and I'm glad Taron is singing. I CAN'T WAIT FOR MAY 31!

text: Okay look, everyone here is saying there should be a David Bowie movie up next after this, and I get that, he's an amazing musician as well, BUT in my humble opinion, there's one guy whom I think should be the main focus in another biopic. The piano man himself, Billy Joel. Seriously, I think it's time he got recognition.  The biopic would chronicle his early life and childhood, showing his early struggles (cold spring harbor, suicide attempt, etc.) and would lead into the creation of some of his most famous albums being created, like Piano Man, The Stranger, or 52nd Street, and show his personal life and struggles that led him to create storm front or river of dreams. I don't know who would play him, I've always thought if Michael Keaton were younger he could nail the looks, but that's just me, I'm still working on that part. I'd also love to see concert he did in Russia re created, right down to the scene of him flipping the piano.  That's just my idea, you may take from it what you like

I was born in Mexico (I know reside in WA state) and I know people kind of judged me because I listened to Elton John, Queen, The Beatles, opera music and definitely modern music like The 1975, The Neighbourhood, Ed Sheeran, Post Malone, 5SOS, etc. versus what most people listen to in my family. But, my dad was the one to introduce me to such iconic people like Elton and although I am not a huge fan, I blame it on pop influence, I know who he is, I listen to his music, I applaud him for what he has done and continues to do. One of my coworkers actually has no idea who this is or even Freddie Mercury, my mind was blown and I was actually angry. I'm 20 and she's only 19.... what the hell
